#Load the data set which is in csv format
data <- read.csv("Impact_of_Remote_Work_on_Mental_Health.csv")

#Convert categorical columns to numeric using manual mapping
data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    Stress_Level = case_when(
      Stress_Level == "Low" ~ 1,
      Stress_Level == "Medium" ~ 2,
      Stress_Level == "High" ~ 3,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    Mental_Health_Condition = case_when(
      Mental_Health_Condition == "None" ~ 0,
      Mental_Health_Condition == "Depression" ~ 1,
      Mental_Health_Condition == "Anxiety" ~ 2,
      Mental_Health_Condition == "Burnout" ~ 3,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    Access_to_Mental_Health_Resources = ifelse(Access_to_Mental_Health_Resources == "Yes", 1, 0),
    Productivity_Change = case_when(
      Productivity_Change == "Increase" ~ 1,
      Productivity_Change == "No Change" ~ 0,
      Productivity_Change == "Decrease" ~ -1,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work = case_when(
      Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work == "Unsatisfied" ~ 1,
      Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work == "Neutral" ~ 2,
      Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work == "Satisfied" ~ 3,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    Physical_Activity = case_when(
      Physical_Activity == "None" ~ 1,
      Physical_Activity == "Weekly" ~ 2,
      Physical_Activity == "Daily" ~ 3,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    Sleep_Quality = case_when(
      Sleep_Quality == "Poor" ~ 1,
      Sleep_Quality == "Average" ~ 2,
      Sleep_Quality == "Good" ~ 3,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ))

#Adding the new calculated columns
data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    # 1. Average Meeting Duration per Week
    Avg_Meeting_Duration_per_Week = ifelse(Number_of_Virtual_Meetings != 0, 
                                           Hours_Worked_Per_Week / Number_of_Virtual_Meetings, NA),
    
    # 2. Experience-to-Age Ratio
    Experience_to_Age_Ratio = ifelse(exists("Age"), Years_of_Experience / Age, NA),
    
    # 3. Work-Life Balance Score
    Work_Life_Balance_Score = (Work_Life_Balance_Rating - Stress_Level + 
                               Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work) / 3,
    
    # 4. Physical and Mental Health Index
    Physical_Mental_Health_Index = (Physical_Activity + Sleep_Quality + 
                                    Access_to_Mental_Health_Resources) / 3,
    
    # 5. Productivity Score (higher score indicates both higher satisfaction and better productivity)
    Productivity_Score = (Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work + Productivity_Change) / 2,
    
    # 6. Work-Life Balance to Stress Ratio
    Work_Life_Balance_to_Stress_Ratio = Work_Life_Balance_Rating / Stress_Level,
    
    # 7. Overall Satisfaction Index
    Overall_Satisfaction_Index = (Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work + Work_Life_Balance_Rating) / 2,

# 8. Meeting Fatigue Score
    Meeting_Fatigue_Score = Number_of_Virtual_Meetings * Avg_Meeting_Duration_per_Week,
    
    # 9. Overtime Indicator - Flag employees who work more than 40 hours a week as working overtime
    Overtime_Indicator = ifelse(Hours_Worked_Per_Week > 40, 1, 0))

Histogram to visualize the age distribution of employees

# Create a ggplot object with data and aesthetics
ggplot(data, aes(x = Age, fill = cut(Age, breaks = c(20, 30, 40, 50, 60)))) + 
  # Add a histogram with specified bin width, black borders, and alignment
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, color = "black", boundary = 0) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("#FFA07A", "#20B2AA", "#FFD700", "#9370DB"), # Define custom colors for each age range
    labels = c("20-30", "30-40", "40-50", "50-60")          # Set custom labels for age ranges
  ) +
  # Customize the x-axis to show ticks at every 5-year interval between 20 and 60
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(20, 60, by = 5)) +
  # Add labels for the title, subtitle, x-axis, y-axis, and legend
  labs(
    title = "Age Distribution",
    subtitle = paste("Total Employees:", nrow(data)),
    x = "Age",
    y = "Number of Employees",
    fill = "Age Range"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  # Further customize the theme for text and alignment
  theme(
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)
  ) +
  ylim(0, 700)

  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("1" = "Low", "2" = "Medium", "3" = "High")) +
  geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = -0.5, size = 4, color = "black") +
  # Apply a minimal theme and customize the text elements
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold", color = "black"),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12, color = "black"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 8, color = "black")
  )

# Pie chart
pie_chart <- ggplot(data, aes(x = "", fill = factor(Sleep_Quality))) +
  # Create a bar chart to be transformed into a pie chart
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "count", color = "white") +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +  
  # Add a title and customize the legend
  labs(title = "Sleep Quality Distribution") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("dodgerblue", "gold", "firebrick2"), 
                    labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")) +
  theme_void() +
  # Customize the title, legend position, and legend text
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold", color = "black"),
    legend.title = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10, color = "black")
  ) +
  # Add percentage labels inside the pie chart slices
  geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = paste0(round((..count..)/sum(..count..)*100, 1), "%")),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 4, color = "black")
grid.arrange(bar_chart, pie_chart, ncol = 2)

# Check the data for NA values
cat("Number of NA values in Meeting_Fatigue_Score:", sum(is.na(data$Meeting_Fatigue_Score)), "\n")
## Number of NA values in Meeting_Fatigue_Score: 327
# Step 1: Create a new categorical variable with proper handling of NA values
data$Fatigue_Category <- cut(
  data$Meeting_Fatigue_Score,
  breaks = c(20, 30, 40, 50, 60),
  labels = c("20-30", "31-40", "41-50", "51-60"),
  include.lowest = TRUE
)

# Handle NA values by assigning them to a separate category
data$Fatigue_Category <- ifelse(
  is.na(data$Meeting_Fatigue_Score),
  "Missing",
  as.character(data$Fatigue_Category)
)

# Convert back to a factor
data$Fatigue_Category <- factor(data$Fatigue_Category, levels = c("20-30", "31-40", "41-50", "51-60", "Missing"))

# Step 2: Bar plot showing the distribution with missing values
bar_plot <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Fatigue_Category)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Meeting Fatigue Score",
    x = "Fatigue Category",
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# Step 3: Density plot for the non-missing values only
density_plot <- ggplot(data[!is.na(data$Meeting_Fatigue_Score), ], aes(x = Meeting_Fatigue_Score)) +
  geom_density(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(
    title = "Density Plot of Meeting Fatigue Score (Excluding Missing Data)",
    x = "Meeting Fatigue Score",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# Step 4: Display the plots together
library(gridExtra)

grid.arrange(bar_plot, density_plot, ncol = 2)

#Impact of Sleep Quality and Physical Activity on Stress

# Prepare the data

stress_health_data <- data %>%
group_by(Sleep_Quality, Physical_Activity, Work_Location) %>%
summarise(
Avg_Stress_Level = mean(Stress_Level, na.rm = TRUE),.groups = "drop") %>%
mutate(Sleep_Quality = factor(Sleep_Quality, levels = c(1, 2, 3), 
labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")), Physical_Activity = factor(Physical_Activity, levels = c(1, 2, 3), labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")), Work_Location = factor(Work_Location, levels = c("Remote", "Hybrid", "Onsite")))
 
# Create the heatmap

ggplot(stress_health_data, aes(x = Physical_Activity, y = Sleep_Quality, fill = Avg_Stress_Level)) +
geom_tile(color = "grey", linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5) +  # Fine gridlines
facet_wrap(~ Work_Location, ncol = 1) +  # Facet by work location
scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("#2B83BA", "#ABDDA4", "#FFFFBF", "#FDAE61", "#D7191C"),  # Gradient from blue to red
name = "Avg Stress Level") + 
  labs(title = "Impact of Sleep Quality and Physical Activity on Stress",
subtitle = "Faceted by Work Location",
x = "Physical Activity Level",
y = "Sleep Quality Rating") + theme_minimal() + theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
strip.text = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
legend.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
legend.text = element_text(size = 10),
panel.grid.major = element_blank(),  # Remove gridlines for cleaner appearance
panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

#Impact of Hours Worked and Stress Level on Work-Life Balance

# Create bins for Hours Worked Per Week
data <- data %>%
  mutate(Hours_Worked_Bin = cut(Hours_Worked_Per_Week, 
                                breaks = c(0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100),
                                labels = c("0–20", "21–40", "41–60", "61–80", "81–100"),
                                include.lowest = TRUE))

# Map numeric Stress Levels to descriptive labels and set order
data <- data %>%
  mutate(Stress_Level_Label = factor(case_when(
    Stress_Level == 1 ~ "Low",
    Stress_Level == 2 ~ "Medium",
    Stress_Level == 3 ~ "High"
  ), levels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")))  # Define the order

# Aggregate data to calculate the average Work-Life Balance Rating
plot_data <- data %>%
  group_by(Hours_Worked_Bin, Stress_Level_Label) %>%
  summarise(Avg_Work_Life_Balance = mean(Work_Life_Balance_Rating, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Hours_Worked_Bin'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
# Plot heatmap
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Hours_Worked_Bin, y = Stress_Level_Label, fill = Avg_Work_Life_Balance)) +
  geom_tile(color = "grey89") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "lightyellow", high = "darkblue", name = "Avg Work-Life \nBalance Rating") +
  labs(
    title = "Impact of Hours Worked and Stress Level on Work-Life Balance",
    subtitle = "Heatmap with grouped Hours Worked",
    x = "Hours Worked (Binned)",
    y = "Stress Level"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold", margin = margin(b = 10)),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, margin = margin(b = 10), hjust = 0.5),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 13, face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "right"
  )
